The Telegraph - Calcutta : Metro

Life

 From fashion zone

 ANUMITA GHOSH

 A model showcases an outfit at the NIFT valedictory function on Tuesday. Picture by Sanjoy Chattopadhyaya 

 What: 

 Valedictory function of Certificate Programme in Application 

 of Information Technology in Fashion and Textiles (Batch 

 II), exclusively for students hailing from the Northeast, 

 sponsored by ministry of development of northeastern region.

 Where: National Institute of Fashion Technology (NIFT), Block LA, Plot 3B, Sector III, Salt Lake.

 When: Tuesday morning.

 Take a look: The event was graced by M.M. Jacob, governor of Meghalaya and other dignitaries. I am sure these youth from the northeastern region have benefited by the training and they will take advantage of the opportunity that the fashion world in this country and abroad offers them, said Jacob.

 An audio-visual round showcased the curriculum and projects undertaken. Forty students from Assam, Meghalaya, Manipur, Mizoram, Nagaland, Arunachal Pradesh, Tripura and Sikkim, who completed the six-month programme, were awarded certificates. Trophies were given away for various categories. Rustom Borbora won the Excellence in IT category. While Aienla N Longkumer won the Best Use of Northeastern Handloom in a Contemporary Style, Regina Chakriinuo walked away with the Best Design Collection award.

 Lalhlimpuii Langel bagged the Best Garment Construction prize. Ramthamghaki Hauzel won the Best Lifestyle Product criteria. For Best Use of Surface Ornamentation Techniques, it was Lahunlang Nongkynrih. The Best Academic Performance was bagged by Ngangom Ranjita Devi.

 A cultural programme followed. Songs, dances it was quite an eclectic mix. Next up was a fashion show. The focus was gowns, pretty, sensuous and trendy. Peach, maroon, green, yellow The palette was a riot of colours. 

 Voiceover: After 

 the feedback we received from the previous batch, we focused 

 on state-specific materials this year. These students have 

 the flair and aptitude for designing. We are looking at 

 a one-year programme that will improve the career prospects 

 of students, smiled Shantmanu, director, NIFT, Calcutta.




